		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> Nemo historicum, aut aliorum fer&egrave; scriptorum, Decori est ubiq[ue] locorum
					obseruantior; aut viuida[e] pariter, seria[e]q[ue] descriptionis tenacior, qu&agrave;m Liuius.
					Ibiq[ue] semper maxim&egrave;, ubi maxim&egrave; opus, aut usus. Tam solerti iudicio est pra[e]ditus, et
					tanta discerione instructus noster historicus: omni verborum.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Livy" />
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> sententiarumq[ue] apparatu passim cultissimus.</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Of the historians, or other writers practically, no-one more observes the 
			decorum of the topics anywhere, than Livy does; and no-one sticks more 
			consistently to a description that is both lively and serious. And especially always there, where it is most needed
			or useful. Such expert judgment our historian possesses and with such discrimination he is equipped -
			he is the most elegant throughout in any display of words and opinions. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> De fortuna, et virtute Romanoru[m], ecc&egrave; prudens, et politicus Plutarchi liber: 
					qui Romana[e] historia[e] lectori utilissimus; Censori, aut critico pernecessarius est. 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Plutarch" />
					<book title="Parallel Lives" />
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation> About the fate and virtue of the Romans see Plutarch's perceptive
			and political book, which is very useful for the reader of Roman history and absolutely essential
			for the evaluator or critic.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>Dionysius Halicarnassaeus Gra[e]c&egrave; de Romanorum initijs, 
					et primis urbis temporibus, ea eleganter, prudenterq[ue] tradit, qua[e] a M. Varrone,
					hero suo acceperat, instructissimo Polyhistore. Gra[e]c&egrave; etiam de rebus Romanis optim&egrave; Polybius,
					Plutarchus, Dion &agrave; quo recentiaora quoq[ue] patefactae. Et, quod ad monarchiam spectat, magis regia.
					Halicarnassaeus, Polybius, Plutarchus, Dion, mea aurea specula rerum Romanarum. Sed ecc&egrave; Liuius, meum 
					adimantinu[m] prisma: cum splendidissimis mundi luminibus, Sallustio, et Ca[e]sare; Tacito, et Suetonio; 
					Valerio Maximo, et Frontino.</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Dionysus of Halicarnassus"/>
					<person name="Marcus Varro" />
					<person name="Polybius"/>
					<person name="Plutarch" />
					<person name="Dio Cassius" />
					<person name="Sallust" />
					<person name="Julius Caesar" />
					<person name="Tacitus" />
					<person name="Suetonius" />
					<person name="Valerius Maximus" />
					<person name="Sextus Julius Frontinus" />		
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Dionysus of Halicarnassus gracefully and perceptively reports in Greek about
			the beginnings of the Romans and the first ages of the City the things he received from his master Marcus 
			Varro, that exceedingly skilled polyhistor. Also in Greek about Roman matters there are Polybius, Plutarch,
			Cassus Dio, who also illuminated more recent times and more royal subjects, when regarding the monarchy.
			Dionysus, Polybius, Plutarch and Dio Cassius are my golden mirrors of Roman matters. Yet see Livy, my 
			rock-solid prism, together with the brightests lights of the world, Sallust and Caesar, Tacitus and 
			Suetonius, Valerius Maximus and Frontinus.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> Qu&ograve;d imprudenter Romani deos Penates, qui Troiam
					custodire non poterant, sibi crediderint profuturos. Augustinus de Civitate Dei. l. I. c. 3.
					Qu&ograve;d eo tempore Aeneas in Italiam venerit, quo Labdon iudex pra[e]sidebat Hebra[e]is. l. 18. c. 19.
					De regibus Latii, quorum primaus &AElig;neas, et duodecimus Aventinus dij facti sunt. l. eod. c. 21.
					An debuerit dijs Iliacis Roma committi. l. 3. c. 8. Qu&ograve;d Romani quosdam sibi Deos non ratione, 
					sed adulatione instituerunt. l. 2. c. 15. </marginalia_text>
					<person name="Augustine" />
					<person name="Aeneas"/>
					<person name="Aventinus"/>
					<person name="Labdon"/>
					<book title="De Civitate Dei" />
					<location name="Troy"/>
					<location name="Rome"/>
					<location name="Italy"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation> How imprudent the Romans were in believing that they might derive any 
			benefit from the Penates (household gods), who could not protect Troy: Augustine City of God, bk. 1, c. 3.
			That Aeneas came to Italy at the time when Labdon presided as judge over the Hebrews: bk 18, c. 19.
			Of the kings of Latium, among whom, Aeneas, the first, and Aventinus, the twelfth, were made gods. The same bk,
			c. 21. Whether Rome ought to be entrusted to the Trojan Gods. Bk. 3, c. 8. That the Romans established certain of their gods 
			through flattery, not reason. bk. 2, c. 15.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
